tochord","Primitive streak","Neural tube"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Enotochord\u003C/strong\u003E is a transient embryonic structure that forms during the third week of development. It develops from the primitive node and extends cranially along the midline of the embryo. The notochord secretes signalling molecules that induce the overlying ectoderm to form the neural plate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esomites\u003C/strong\u003E are blocks of mesoderm that form on either side of the neural tube and give rise to skeletal muscle, vertebrae and dermis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efloor plate\u003C/strong\u003E is a specialised region at the ventral midline of the neural tube that develops after neural tube formation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimitive streak\u003C/strong\u003E appears earlier in development and establishes the embryonic axis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural tube\u003C/strong\u003E forms later through neurulation of the neural plate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe notochord largely degenerates during development, with its remnants forming the nucleus pulposus of the intervertebral discs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The notochord induces formation of the neural plate through secretion of signalling molecules during embryological development.","The notochord develops from the primitive node and extends cranially during week three of development.","The notochord later degenerates to form the nucleus pulposus of intervertebral discs."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"ite